Black still wants to advance his d-pawn, but in the meantime he takes control of the b5-square in case it might be necessary to take on d5 with his c-pawn.
Black succeeds in carrying out his plan, but its outcome is unclear

!  White  is maintaining the tension quite resourcefully.  16. exd5 Nfxd5= would be bland.

! Likewise resourceful, Black makes what Nimzovich termed a "mysterious rook move,"  transferring his rook to the potentially open file, thus making the capture of d5 less appetizing for White.  Moreover, the move is useful against White's coming attempt.
Otherwise, the weakness on d5 would have been balanced by a weakness of d4.
